SIMPLE: plump
RECORDS: 5

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Plump
<hw>Plump</hw> <pr>(pl⟦ucr⟧mp)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Plumper</adjf>
<pr>(pl⟦ucr⟧mp"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Plumpest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>plomp</ets> rude,
clumsy; akin to D. <ets>plomp</ets>, G., Dan., & Sw. <ets>plump</ets>;
probably of imitative origin. Cf. <er>Plump</er>, <pos>adv.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Well rounded or filled out; full; fleshy; fat; <as>as,
a <ex>plump</ex> baby; <ex>plump</ex> cheeks.</as></def>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The god of wine did his <qex>plump</qex> clusters bring.</q>
<rj><qau>T. Carew.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Done or made plump, or suddenly and without
reservation; blunt; unreserved; direct; downright.</def></p>

<p><q>After the <qex>plump</qex> statement that the author was at
Erceldoune and spake with Thomas.</q>
<rj><qau>Saintsbury.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plump</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Plump
<hw>Plump</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A knot; a cluster; a group; a crowd;
a flock; <as>as, a <ex>plump</ex> of trees, fowls, or spears</as>.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To visit islands and the <qex>plumps</qex> of men.</q>
<rj><qau>Chapman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plump</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Plump
<hw>Plump</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Cf. D. <ets>plompen</ets>, G.
<ets>plumpen</ets>, Sw. <ets>plumpa</ets>, Dan. <ets>plumpe</ets>. See
<er>Plump</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To grow plump; to
swell out; <as>as, her cheeks have <ex>plumped</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To drop or fall suddenly or heavily, all at
once.</def>⟦ldquo⟧Dulcissa <xex>plumps</xex> into a chair.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Spectator.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To <er>give</er> a plumper. See <er>Plumper</er>,
2.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plump</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Plump
<hw>Plump</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Plumped</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Plumping</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make plump; to
fill (out) or support; -- often with <xex>up</xex>.</def><-- as, to
<ex>plump up</ex> the pillows -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>plump</qex> up the hollowness of their history with
improbable miracles.</q> <rj><qau>Fuller.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To cast or let drop all at once, suddenly and
heavily; <as>as, to <ex>plump</ex> a stone into water</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To give (a vote), as a plumper. See
<er>Plumper</er>, 2.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plump</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 5 ====
HEADWORD: Plump
<hw>Plump</hw>, <pos>adv.</pos> <ety>[Cf. D. <ets>plomp</ets>, interj.,
G. <ets>plump</ets>, <ets>plumps</ets>. Cf. <er>Plump</er>, <pos>a. &
v.</pos>]</ety> <def>Directly; suddenly; perpendicularly.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Fall <xex>plump</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Beau. & Fl.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Plumper</ent>⟦br⟧
